Version control with Git and GitHub

Sonia Mazzi - Data Science Campus - ONS

05 November, 2019





1 Introduction

Sharing code is as important as sharing data for transparency and reproducibility.

Many analysts and researchers self-learn coding and are not trained in software-engineering standards about how to document code, writing etiquette and testing. However, the fact that code is not written to a high standard should not prevent code sharing. The benefits of open code outweigh the potential unpleasantness experienced by the expert code writer.

Publications that make the used code available have, generally higher impact than publications where code is not available.

One important tool for code quality and code sharing is a version control system (VCS).

A version control system is a tool that manages changes made to the files and directories in a project.

Git, together with GitHub, is one such VCS tool.

1.1 Intended audience

The target audience for this training is someone who analyses data by writing code (e.g. in R or Python), at intermediate to advanced level, but is new to version control systems.

Git was built to manage development of the Linux kernel, which is probably very different from what the intended audience does. Most people need a small subset of Git’s functionality and that is the focus of this workshop. At the end of this document there are references that give a more comprehensive explanation of Git uses.

Pre-requisites are:

  • Have a good grasp of files and directories and be generally knowledgeable about where things live on your computer.

  • We will work on the command line or shell, so you should know how to open up a shell. Desirable is also that you know how to navigate to a certain directory and list the files there.


2 Git and GitHub

Git is software used for version control system. It was developed to aid groups working collaboratively in software development. Git keeps track of changes of a set of files.

A Git project has two components:

  • one is the files and directories that are created, added to a project and edited,

  • the other one is the information that Git records about the project’s history.

The combination of the two is called a repository, or “repo”, for short. The information about the repo’s history is in a directory called .git located in the root directory of the repository. Git expects the repo’s information to be of a very precise form, so never edit or delete anything in .git.

Git has now been redeployed by data scientists to keep track of the changes of the many files that compose a data science project: data, figures, reports, code, and any files that change over time or need to be shared can and should be stored and shared using a VCS like Git.

Some useful features of Git are:

  • Nothing that is saved to Git is ever lost, so you can always go back to see which results were generated by which versions of your programs.

  • Git automatically notifies you when your work conflicts with someone else’s, so it is harder to accidentally overwrite work.

  • Git can synchronize work done by different people on different machines.



GitHub is a web-based graphical user interface (GUI) which makes viewing and interacting with a repository for some simple tasks (such as file edits and adding files to the repo) possible. GitHub is a “Git-aware” home for repositories in the web that simplifies collaboration.



3 Real-life project and Git version-controlled (VC) project

A real-life project is simply the collection of files that make up a project. These are a collection of files stored in a folder.

The Git VC version of a project contains the history of your files, the version-controlled collection.

Both versions live in your local computer.

How do you go from the real-life project to the Git VC project?

Let us illustrate how this works.

EXERCISE. Creating a local repo.

  1. In your Documents folder create a new folder named “practice_git_repo”.

  2. Go to the command line and use cd to make sure that you are in “Documents/practice_git_repo”.

  3. The repo is empty. Type the command dir /a (ls -la in a Mac) and ensure this is so.

  4. Now type the command git init. This is turning the folder into a version-controlled repo.

  5. Type the command dir /a (ls -la in a Mac) to list all files in the folder. You should see now a .git directory listed. (Note that dir (ls in Mac) will not show the .git directory).

You can now add as many files as you wish to the folder in the usual/preferred way. The added files will not be part of the Git VC repo. To add the files to the Git VC repo and save them (we call this saving action “commit”) we proceed as follows.

3.1 Adding files to a Git VC repo

The process of adding files to your repo is a two-step process: first add files to a “staging area”, then commit the files to permanent storage.

The staging area stores files with changes that need to be saved but haven’t been saved yet. Putting files in the staging area is like putting things in a box, while committing those changes is like putting that box in the post: one can add more things to the box or take things out as often as you want, but once you’ve put it in the post, you can’t make further changes. But you will be able to edit, save, add and commit again in the future.



Adding files to a Git repo.



Let us illustrate how this works in practice.

EXERCISE. From simple files to tracked files.

  1. Open RStudio, then Session > Set Working Directory > Choose Directory, and choose “practice_git_repo”.

  2. Now, File > New File > R markdown, accept all the options without change and click OK.

  3. Save the file, File > Save , name the file “some_code”. This is an R markdown file and so its full name is “some_code.Rmd”.

  4. Click the “Knit” icon. This will compile the code to produce an html file. This html will open in a viewer. Look at the html output and then close it.

  5. Now go back to the command line and type dir (ls in Mac). This will list all the files in the folder. You should see that now there are two new files: “some_code.Rmd” and “some_code.html” and a folder “some_code_files”. These files are in your real-life repo but not in your Git VC repo yet.

  6. Verify this by executing the command git status which should give an output like

On branch master

No commits yet

Untracked files:
  (use "git add <file>..." to include in what will be committed)

    some_code.Rmd
    some_code.html
    some_code_files/

nothing added to commit but untracked files present (use "git add" to track)
  1. Add the files to the Git VC repo:

    • git add . (this stages all the files in “practice_git_repo”)

    • git commit -m "initial commit" (this commits the staged files. Commits must always have a message)

    • git status (this shows details of the git repository, including changes to files) should show an output like

      On branch master
nothing to commit, working tree clean

      Now, all the files in the repo are being tracked (version-controlled) by Git.


  1. Go back to RStudio and add some text to the “some_code.Rmd” by typing “Hello” next to “## R Markdown”. Click on the “Knit” button. Now the files in the repo have been modified.

  2. Go to the Command Prompt and type git status. What do you see?

  3. Now we will only add the files “some_code.Rmd” and “some_code.html”. Type git add some_code.*.

  4. Type git status. What do you see?

  5. Type git commit. This time you didn’t write a commit message and, since a commit message is mandatory, you are sent to an editor. Type a commit message. To write and quit the editor type: “:” (colon), look at the bottom of the editor window, type “wq!”. Now you should be back at the command prompt.

  6. Go back to RStudio, add the text “there” next to “## R Markdown Hello”, press the “Knit” button. Now, on the Command Prompt type git diff some_code.Rmd. What do you see?

  7. On your own, add the changed file “some_code.Rmd” only to the “practice_git_repo” repo.



Some useful git commands are

  • git status shows you which files are in this staging area, and which files have changes that haven’t yet been added to it.

  • In order to compare the file as it currently is to what you last saved (committed), use git diff filename.

  • git diff without any file names will give all the changes in the repo.

  • git diff mydirectory will show the changes to the files in the directory named mydirectory.

4 Sharing a repo

Once your local Git VC repo has been updated (save > add > commit), it can be shared with the rest of the world by placing it in “the cloud”, for example in GitHub.com. Proceed as follows.

EXERCISE. Creating a remote repo in GitHub.

  1. You have a folder with project files locally in your computer. In this example, the folder, a Git repo, is “practice_git_repo”.

  2. After creating an account in GitHub, create a repo in GitHub with the same name as your folder.

    • Go to https://github.com and log in to your GitHub account.

    • On the “Repositories” field on the left click the green button “New”. Or, if you are on your own profile page, click on “Repositories”, then click the green “New” button.

    • Specify

      • Repository name: “practice_git_repo”

      • Description: “Learning Git/GitHub”

      • Public.

      • Don’t initialize this repository with a README.

      • For everything else, just accept the default.

    • Click the green button “Create repository”.

  3. Copy the HTTPS clone URL to your clipboard via the green “Clone or Download” button.

  4. Go back to GitHub and check that your repo has been populated.


Now we have the local Git VC repo with all the files already committed and a remote repo in GitHub which is empty at the moment. We use Git to upload (push) the Git VC repo to GitHub.



Essential dynamics of project file management using Git and GitHub: push and pull repos.



To upload the repo, in the Terminal, shell or command line, proceed as follows.

EXERCISE. Uploading a local repo to GitHub.

  1. git remote add origin https://github.com/your_username/practice_git_repo.git This tells Git where the remote repo is, the location of the repo in “the cloud”. The url can be pasted from your clipboard.

  2. git push -u origin master This will populate the remote repo with the project files and their history).


Depending on the permissions you set for your repo, now other people can interact with your new GitHub repo. Others can browse the repo, see the evolution of it, clone it to their own computers (creating a local repo), update it, make changes, and propose changes (raise issues).


5 Some Git/Github workflows

5.1 A team member makes changes to the GitHub repo and you want to update your local repo

Continue with the same example.

Recall that when the remote repo “practice_git_repo” was created in GitHub a README.md file was not created.

A README.md file now will be added in the GitHub remote repo (pretend a collaborator made the change in their local repo and pushed their changes to GitHub).

  1. Make sure that within GitHub you are in your repo’s site (https://github.com/your_username/practice_git_repo.git).

  2. Click on the green button “Add a README”. This will open an editor. Add the message “adding README” and commit the changes by clicking on the green button “Commit changes” at the bottom of the page . It is good practice to always add a message to commits.

  3. You should see that now the file README.md is in the (remote) repo.

In order to update your local repo proceed as follows

  1. In the command line type git pull. The output looks something like
remote: Enumerating objects: 4, done.
remote: Counting objects: 100% (4/4), done.
remote: Compressing objects: 100% (2/2), done.
Unpacking objects: 100% (3/3), done.
remote: Total 3 (delta 0), reused 0 (delta 0), pack-reused 0
From github.com:your_username/practice_git_repo
   a545d65..9c96d05  master     -> origin/master
Updating a545d65..9c96d05
Fast-forward
 README.md | 2 ++
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+)
 create mode 100644 README.md
  1. List the files in the repo using dir (ls in Mac).

You have synced the local and remote repos now.


5.2 You make changes to the local repo and want to update (push) the remote repo

This is an exercise for you.

  1. Go back to RStudio.

  2. Add the following text at the end of the file “some_code.Rmd”.

```{r}

plot(cars)

```

This is called an R chunk and it produces a scatter plot of the variables in the data frame cars.

  1. Now save the file by clicking on the “diskette” icon. You can also “Knit” it to see the html output.

  2. Update the GitHub remote repo with the changes. You do this alone now.


Now, a few points of advice

  • Make local changes, save, add, commit

Do this every time you finish a valuable chunk of work, probably many times a day.

  • Push your local changes to GitHub

Do this a few times a day, but possibly less often than you commit.

  • Before you push your local changes into GitHub, pull from GitHub

In general (and especially when collaborating with other project team members) you will usually need to pull changes from the remote (GitHub) before pushing the local changes you have made. The reason is that before you push your changes you want to get the changes that someone in your team has made and pushed before you. For this reason, it’s a good idea to try and get into the habit of pulling before you attempt to push.

  • Use git fetch if you want to see what everybody else has been working on before incorporating those changes in your local repo.

The git fetch command downloads commits, files, etc. from a remote repository into your local repo.
Git isolates fetched content from existing local content; it has absolutely no effect on your local development work. Fetched content has to be explicitly checked out using the git checkout command. This makes fetching a safe way to review commits before integrating them with your local repository.



6 Branching

Suppose that one of your project files is ready but you would like to experiment with or edit it further. This situation can arise, for example, if someone else in your team has produced a code or a report and you would like to propose some changes for the consideration of the other team members before the team decides to incorporate these changes.

Technically, branching is the way to work on different versions of a repository at one time.

By default, a repository has one branch named “master” which is the branch containing the final or “official” versions of the project files.

When you create a branch off the master branch, you are making a copy, or snapshot, of master as it was at that point in time. If someone else made changes to the master branch while you were working on your branch, you could pull in those updates.



Essential dynamics of project file management using Git and GitHub: branching. Picture from GitHub.com



6.1 Workflow to work with branches

  • To create a new branch using Git and switch to it at the same time, run the git checkout command with the -b switch:

git checkout -b name_of_new_branch

  • Make changes in the new branch and commit all your changes.

  • To switch back to your master branch:

git checkout master

  • In order to merge name_of_new_branch with master

git merge name_of_new_branch

  • If you don’t need the branch anymore it can be deleted.

git branch -d name_of_new_branch


6.2 Pull-Requests

Create a pull-request to propose and collaborate on changes to a repository. These changes are proposed in a branch, which ensures that the master branch only contains finished and approved work.

To tell others about changes you have pushed to a branch in a repository you issue a pull-request. Once a pull-request is opened, you can discuss and review the potential changes with collaborators and add follow-up commits before your changes are merged into the base branch.

The workflow is as follows:

  • A developer creates the feature in a dedicated branch in their local repo.

  • The developer pushes the branch to a repository.

  • The developer files a pull-request.

  • The rest of the team reviews the code, discusses it, and alters it.

  • The project maintainer merges the feature into the official repository and closes the pull request.

Creating the pull-request

  • On GitHub, navigate to the main page of the repository.

  • In the “Branch” menu, choose the branch that contains your commits.

  • Branch dropdown menu: To the right of the Branch menu, click “New pull request”.

  • After your pull request has been reviewed, it can be merged into the repository.

Git has a command git request-pull. It generates a formatted text saying since a commit there are new changes and the changes are available at a branch of a url. The patch can be included in the text too. After receiving this text, the receiver can run git fetch <url> <branch> to get the changes.

# Ignoring certain file types

Git sees every file in your local repo as one of three things:

* *Tracked*: files which have been added and committed.

* *Untracked*: files which have not been staged or committed.

* *Ignored*: files which Git has been told to ignore.

<br>

Why ignore files?

Ignored files are usually machine generated files, for example the output of a source code.
These files can be derived from the source files in the repo or should otherwise not be committed. 

For example, when using html R markdown the .Rmd file is the source code and when compiled (knitted) it produces an html file. html files cannot be viewed in GitHub and what you see is the raw html, which is not pretty. For that reason it is recommended that html files are not version controlled. A work around this issue is presented in the workshop "Version controlled R projects - using Git and GitHub from RStudio".

Another example of files that should be ignored so they don't clutter your repo unnecessarily are .log and .aux files generated when compiling .tex files (e.g. when using LaTeX).

Ignored files are tracked in a special file named .gitignore that is checked in at the root of your repository. There is no explicit git ignore command: instead the .gitignore file must be edited and committed by hand when you have new files that you wish to ignore. .gitignore files contain patterns that are matched against file names in your repository to determine whether or not they should be ignored.

<br>

**EXERCISE** Continuing to work with the repo "practice_git_repo", we will edit the .gitignore file and tell Git to ignore .html files. Since we already have committed an html file, if we don't want it in the repo we must delete it manually.

In the Terminal:

1. Add the line *.html to .gitignore. This will ignore any file with a .html extension.

`
echo *.html >> .gitignore
` 

2. Manually remove the .html files from the local repo.

`
git rm --cached *.html
` 

3. Commit the changes.

`
git commit -m "Start ignoring .html files"
`
 Output looks like

[master 3ccd90f] Start ignoring .html files 1 file changed, 433 deletions(-) delete mode 100644 some_code.html


4. Push the changes to GitHub

`
git push
`

Output looks like

Enumerating objects: 3, done. Counting objects: 100% (3/3), done. Delta compression using up to 4 threads Compressing objects: 100% (2/2), done. Writing objects: 100% (2/2), 234 bytes | 234.00 KiB/s, done. Total 2 (delta 1), reused 0 (delta 0) remote: Resolving deltas: 100% (1/1), completed with 1 local object. To github.com:sonjam111/practice_git_repo.git 74f0a7c..3ccd90f master -> master

# Time travel: Returning to an older version of the repo

Go to http://github.com/your_username/practice_git_repo

To view the history of the repo click on "X commits" where X is some number.

Here you will see all the commits and the messages for those commits on the left column. Now you should understand why those messages in each commit are made and why they should be informative.

On the right column there are numbers. These numbers are the "SHA" (Secure Hash Algorithm) or "Hash" numbers.  Each time a commit is made Git creates a unique ID, the SHA or hash, which keeps a record of what changes were made, when and by who.

Also in the right column there is an icon with "<>" symbols. By clicking on this icon you can browse the status of the repo when a commit was made.

Now, we will return to the original version of "some_code.Rmd", the one in the very first commit that was made.

1. Copy the SHA number of the first commit to the clipboard by clicking in the clipboard icon.

2. Go to the shell, command line or Terminal and type
 
`
git checkout YYY some_code.Rmd
`

where YYY is the SHA number in your clipboard.

3. Type `git status`. The output should look something like

On branch master Your branch is up to date with ‘origin/master’.

Changes to be committed: (use “git reset HEAD …” to unstage)

modified:   some_code.Rmd

Untracked files: (use “git add …” to include in what will be committed)

.gitignore

``` So, we see that now “some_code.Rmd” has been modified by reverting the file to its original version. We also see that these changes still need to be added and committed.

  1. Add and commit in the usual way

git add .

git commit -m "revert some_code.Rmd to original"

git push

  1. Go back to the repo GitHub webpage and click on the file to see its restored contents.



7 Cleaning up

At the end of this course you should clean up in GitHub and in the training laptop by deleting the repos.

Local: When you’re ready to clean up, you can delete the local repo any way you like. It is just a regular directory on your computer.

Here is how to do that in the shell, if current working directory is practice_git_repo:

cd ..

rm -rf practice_git_repo/

GitHub: In the browser, go to the repo’s page on GitHub. Click on “Settings”.

Scroll down, click on “delete repository,” and do as it asks.
